<div class=3D"page-header">
    <h1>
        <span class=3D"visible-print">Paul Hammant's Blog: </span>
        The limits of merging experiment
       =20
        <div class=3D"visible-print" style=3D"width:100%;height:4px;border:=
2px solid #000;">
    </div></h1>
    <div></div>
</div>

<div class=3D"row">
    <div class=3D"span8">
       =20
        <p>A colleague suggested the cherry-picking way for trunk-based-dev=
elopment with branch for release needs worked examples cos there are foot-g=
uns.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Cherry-pick to a release branch isn=E2=80=99t crystal clear as a workf=
low</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The failure modes are more interesting than they look. To pick at it, I =
built a small playground - a single-file Sinatra CRUD app, an end-to-end Pl=
aywright test,=20
and a series of trunk commits that would let me run the same scenario two d=
ifferent ways and see what git actually does.</p>

<p>The repo is here: <a href=3D"https://github.com/paul-hammant/limits-of-m=
erging-experiment">paul-hammant/limits-of-merging-experiment</a>.=20
Clone it, run <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">./start.=
sh</code> to make <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">solu=
tion/</code> folder the git folder not the one you cloned.</p>

<p>The run <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bundle inst=
all</code> to go get deps.</p>

<h2 id=3D"the-setup">The setup</h2>

<p>Folder <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">solution/</c=
ode> contains the ruby/sinatra app and a playwright test for it. It is thre=
e tier - html with JS, a ruby middle tier, and a sqlite base tier.  <code c=
lass=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">reset.sh</code> will
keep getting us back to a starting point. See =E2=80=9CC1=E2=80=9D below.</=
p>

<p>Five hypothetical trunk commits, all reachable as patches in <code class=
=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">patches/</code> and re-applicable=
 on demand, are key to this experiment.</p>

<table class=3D"table table-striped">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>&nbsp;</th>
      <th>Change</th>
      <th>Touches</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C1</strong></td>
      <td>Initial Person CRUD app, seeded Flintstones, Playwright happy-pat=
h test</td>
      <td>everything</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C2</strong></td>
      <td>Add <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">hair_col=
or</code> (string) - dropdown, JS validation, DB <code class=3D"language-pl=
aintext highlighter-rouge">CHECK</code> constraint</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">app.rb</code=
>, <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">happy_path_test.rb<=
/code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C3</strong></td>
      <td>Button text change to UPPERCASE: NEW PERSON / EDIT / DELETE / SAV=
E / CANCEL</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">app.rb</code=
>, <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">happy_path_test.rb<=
/code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C4</strong></td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">hair_color</=
code> becomes <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">INTEGER<=
/code> (1..6); dropdown values are now ints</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">app.rb</code=
>, <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">happy_path_test.rb<=
/code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C5</strong></td>
      <td>Add maintainer comment in header (cosmetic, previously untouched =
region)</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">app.rb</code=
></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The shape that matters for this experiment: <strong>C3 is cosmetic and u=
nrelated to hair colour. C4 builds on C2. C5 is in an untouched corner.</st=
rong> This is normal trunk=20
life - small unrelated changes interleaving in the same files.</p>

<p>The hypothetical release branch is cut from <strong>C2</strong>. The tea=
m wishes that was it for the release, and continues on an unfrozen trunk as=
 normal. Later there=E2=80=99s something
that agreed as a bug fix (definately not feature creep) and it should be ch=
erry picked to the release branch by the responsible =E2=80=9Cmerge meister=
=E2=80=9D or release engineer.
We want to ship bugfix C4 (the int conversion) but not C3 feature change (t=
he uppercase buttons).</p>

<h2 id=3D"scenario-1-git-am-is-honest-and-thats-why-it-fails">Scenario 1: <=
code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git am</code> is honest=
, and that=E2=80=99s why it fails</h2>

<p>First release engineer instinct: apply the C4 patch directly to =E2=80=
=9Cstable=E2=80=9D release branch.</p>

<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>$ git checkout -b release c2
$ git am patches/c4-hair-color-int.patch
Applying: C4: hair_color stored as INTEGER (1..6), dropdown values become i=
nts
error: patch failed: app.rb:133
error: app.rb: patch does not apply
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Loud failure. Why? Look at the failing hunk:</p>

<div class=3D"language-diff highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight"><pr=
e class=3D"highlight"><code>       &lt;td&gt;&lt;%=3D h p['dob'] %&gt;&lt;/=
td&gt;
<span class=3D"gd">-      &lt;td&gt;&lt;%=3D h p['hair_color'] %&gt;&lt;/td=
&gt;
</span><span class=3D"gi">+      &lt;td&gt;&lt;%=3D h(HAIR_COLORS[p['hair_c=
olor']]) %&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
</span>       &lt;td class=3D"row-actions"&gt;
         &lt;a class=3D"button" href=3D"/people/&lt;%=3D p['id'] %&gt;/edit=
"&gt;EDIT&lt;/a&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The patch=E2=80=99s <em>context lines</em> (the unchanged <code class=3D=
"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">EDIT</code> reference <strong>around=
</strong> the change) include C3=E2=80=99s uppercase text. On the release b=
ranch the buttons still say <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-r=
ouge">Edit</code>. Context doesn=E2=80=99t match. <code class=3D"language-p=
laintext highlighter-rouge">git am</code> is strict about context - it refu=
ses.</p>

<p>This is <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git am</cod=
e> correctly doing its job. It=E2=80=99s not the failure mode I=E2=80=99m i=
nterested in.</p>

<h2 id=3D"scenario-2-git-cherry-pick-is-helpful-and-thats-why-it-lies">Scen=
ario 2: <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git cherry-pic=
k</code> is helpful, and that=E2=80=99s why it lies</h2>

<p>(we do a <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">./reset.sh=
</code> to go back to the starting position)</p>

<p>Second instinct, and what most developers actually type:</p>

<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>$ git checkout -b release c2
$ git cherry-pick c4
Auto-merging app.rb
[release ...] C4: hair_color stored as INTEGER (1..6), dropdown values beco=
me ints
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Clean. No conflict. Test passes.</p>

<p>Why? Because <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git ch=
erry-pick</code> doesn=E2=80=99t apply patches by context - it does a three=
-way merge with the parent of C4 as the merge base. The merger sees:</p>

<ul>
  <li>merge base (C3 on trunk) had <code class=3D"language-plaintext highli=
ghter-rouge">EDIT</code></li>
  <li>the cherry-pick target (release branch) has <code class=3D"language-p=
laintext highlighter-rouge">Edit</code></li>
  <li>C4 didn=E2=80=99t change either of those lines</li>
</ul>

<p>So three-way merge correctly concludes =E2=80=9Cleave the case alone, ju=
st apply the hair-colour change.=E2=80=9D Release ends up with C4=E2=80=99s=
 diff cleanly applied on top of <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlight=
er-rouge">Edit</code>.</p>

<p>That=E2=80=99s the textbook good outcome. <strong>And it=E2=80=99s exact=
ly the failure mode the colleague was warning about</strong> - not because =
<em>this</em> cherry-pick was wrong, but because the=20
success was contingent on a property of the diffs that nobody checked. C3 h=
appened to touch only button text. If C3 had ever-so-slightly tidied up the=
 dropdown the=20
cherry pick may have conflicted - forcing a human to arbitrate on it.</p>

<p>The lies are little lies, from good intentions, perhaps.</p>

<h2 id=3D"what-about-merge-point-tracking">What about merge-point tracking?=
</h2>

<p>Here=E2=80=99s where Subversion fans get nostalgic. SVN=E2=80=99s <code =
class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">svn:mergeinfo</code> tries t=
o record on the release branch =E2=80=9CI have integrated revisions r3, r4 =
from trunk.=E2=80=9D=20
A subsequent sweep merge of trunk into release knows to skip those.  Not ju=
st Subversion, but the =E2=80=9Cbigger=E2=80=9D VCS technologies Perforce a=
nd Microsoft=E2=80=99s TFVC.</p>

<p>Git has none of that. A cherry-pick produces a commit with a different S=
HA from the original - <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"=
>git cat-file -p</code> on the two reveals different parents,=20
different trees, different hashes. The only audit trail is the optional <co=
de class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">(cherry picked from commi=
t ...)</code> line that <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge=
">git cherry-pick -x</code> leaves in the=20
commit message, and <strong>git itself does not consult that line for anyth=
ing</strong>. It=E2=80=99s a comment.</p>

<p>So if you later merge trunk wholly into release, git=E2=80=99s merge bas=
e is the last common ancestor - which is <strong>C2</strong>, not C4.=20
Git will re-apply C3, C4, and C5 from trunk on top of release. If the cherr=
y-picked C4 on release is byte-identical to trunk=E2=80=99s C4, the merger =
deduplicates=20
silently. If they differ even slightly (a hotfix on release, a typo correct=
ion), you get spurious conflicts that look very real, with no way for git t=
o say=20
=E2=80=9Cyou already integrated this, just take trunk=E2=80=99s copy.=E2=80=
=9D Coming from Svn, Perforce or TFVC merge-point-tracking is not as you re=
member it. In a TBD + release branches workflow you would <strong>never</st=
rong> do a sweeping commit from trunk to the release branch - you would onl=
y do cherry picks and less and less so over time to that release branch.=20
At some point the release branch has been superceded and eleigible for dele=
tion.</p>

<p>SVN=E2=80=99s mergeinfo aimed at this and got bitten by edge cases - sub=
tree mergeinfo creep, properties getting out of sync if you bypass <code cl=
ass=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">svn merge</code>. The=20
=E2=80=9Cslightly broken=E2=80=9D reputation is earned. But the <em>intent<=
/em> - cross-branch awareness of what=E2=80=99s been integrated - is someth=
ing git deliberately doesn=E2=80=99t have.=20
Linus rejected it on simplicity grounds. The price is paid by anyone runnin=
g long-lived release branches.</p>

<h2 id=3D"the-order-of-cherry-picks-question">The order of cherry-picks que=
stion</h2>

<p>If C3 and C4 are eventually both wanted on the release branch, does the =
order matter? Two scenarios:</p>

<p><strong>Scenario A - out of order.</strong> Cherry-pick C4 first (the ur=
gent fix), then C3 later (because someone decided uppercase buttons should =
ship after all):</p>

<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>release branch cherry-picks: C2 then C4' t=
hen C3'
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>Scenario B - in order.</strong> Cherry-pick in trunk order:</p>

<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>release branch cherry-picks: C2 then C3' t=
hen  C4'
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>In both cases, trunk has C2, C3, and C4. We could then sweep-merge c5 fr=
om trunk into the release branch.</p>

<p>Resulting tree hashes (with author/date/identity pinned so SHAs are dete=
rministic):</p>

<table class=3D"table table-striped">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>&nbsp;</th>
      <th>Tree hash after sweep merge</th>
      <th>Merge commit SHA</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Scenario A (out of order)</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">088b679...</=
code></td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">e96a8e0...</=
code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Scenario B (in order)</td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">088b679...</=
code></td>
      <td><code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">4ad3efc...</=
code> (fast-forward!)</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Tree hashes match. Content is byte-identical.</strong> Empty <co=
de class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git diff</code> between t=
he two release branches.</p>

<p>But the commit graphs are different shapes. Scenario A produced a real m=
erge commit with two parents - the cherry-picked C4=E2=80=99/C3=E2=80=99 on=
 release and the trunk C5 -=20
because the histories diverged. Scenario B=E2=80=99s cherry-picks produced =
commits byte-identical to trunk=E2=80=99s (same diffs, same pinned timestam=
ps), so the sweep merge=20
fast-forwarded; release=E2=80=99s tip <em>is</em> main=E2=80=99s tip.</p>

<p>So the answer to =E2=80=9Cdoes order matter=E2=80=9D is layered:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Content:</strong> no, both converge to the same source tree.<=
/li>
  <li><strong>History shape:</strong> yes, you get a merge node in one and =
a flat history in the other.</li>
  <li><strong>SHA equivalence:</strong> no, never - parent chains differ, s=
o commit SHAs cascade differently. SHA equality was never the right test fo=
r =E2=80=9Cdid this work.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"what-the-sha-actually-proves">What the SHA actually proves</h2>

<p>This is the bit I had to stop and think about. I=E2=80=99d been comparin=
g commit SHAs and getting confused by the differences. The right framing:</=
p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Commit SHA equality means =E2=80=9Cbyte-identical commit object includ=
ing parents.=E2=80=9D Tree hash equality means =E2=80=9Cbyte-identical cont=
ent.=E2=80=9D Cherry-picks change parents. They cannot preserve commit SHAs=
. They can preserve tree hashes - and that=E2=80=99s the only equivalence t=
hat matters for correctness.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>So when judging whether a cherry-pick + sweep merge produced the right r=
esult: <strong>diff the trees, not the commits</strong>. A clean <code clas=
s=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git diff main release</code> aft=
er the sweep is the=20
only proof you need.</p>

<h2 id=3D"what-git-cant-tell-you">What git can=E2=80=99t tell you</h2>

<p>Putting it together, here is what git silently <em>cannot</em> answer fo=
r a release branch built from cherry-picks:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>=E2=80=9CHave I already integrated this trunk commit?=E2=80=
=9D</strong> Git=E2=80=99s answer is =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D - even if you che=
rry-picked it. The DAG has no link after the even (ignoring formatted comme=
nts).</li>
  <li><strong>=E2=80=9CWhen I sweep merge runk to release, will it be a no-=
op?=E2=80=9D</strong> Only if every cherry-picked patch is byte-identical t=
o its trunk twin. There=E2=80=99s no machine check.</li>
  <li><strong>=E2=80=9CAre these two release branches functionally equivale=
nt?=E2=80=9D</strong> Only <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-ro=
uge">git diff</code> of trees can tell you. Commit history is misleading.</=
li>
  <li><strong>=E2=80=9CDid this cherry-pick land safely?=E2=80=9D</strong> =
Only your automated tests can tell you. Three-way merge succeeding is neces=
sary, not sufficient.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id=3D"the-real-risk-in-real-corporate-codebases">The real risk in real =
corporate codebases</h2>

<p>A common pushback: =E2=80=9Cin a million-line corporate codebase, two un=
related commits almost never touch the same file region - cherry-picks land=
 cleanly the vast majority of the=20
time.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s empirically true. The base rate of textual co=
llision is low.</p>

<p>But the question isn=E2=80=99t frequency, it=E2=80=99s <strong>severity =
when it does happen</strong>. The classic bad outcome isn=E2=80=99t a noisy=
 <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git am</code> rejecti=
on - it=E2=80=99s a quiet <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rou=
ge">git cherry-pick</code>=20
that three-way-merges into wrong-but-plausible code, ships to a release bra=
nch, passes your tests because the tests don=E2=80=99t cover the exact corn=
er that broke,=20
and surfaces in production a week later. Git gives you no warning. There=E2=
=80=99s no <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git fsck --=
semantic</code>.</p>

<p>The mitigations I keep coming back to:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Work in thin vertical slices.</strong> This is a good idea ge=
nerally, but it especially pays off when cherry-picks are in your future. A=
 single commit/PR that changes the DB schema, the middle tier, and the UI t=
ogether is one cherry-pick - either it all lands on the release branch or n=
one of it does. Split the same bug fix across three commits (one per tier) =
and you now have three cherry-picks that each have to be remembered, ordere=
d, and applied. Miss one and you ship a half-fix; the release branch compil=
es, the smoke test passes, and the bug is =E2=80=9Cfixed=E2=80=9D everywher=
e except the layer you forgot. Your pre-commit automated tests on the relea=
se branch should catch the omission - but =E2=80=9Cshould=E2=80=9D is doing=
 heavy lifting there, and the failure mode is exactly the kind of partial-s=
tate subtlety tests are weakest at.</li>
  <li><strong>Test the release branch like it=E2=80=99s a fresh codebase</s=
trong>, not =E2=80=9Ctrunk minus a few commits.=E2=80=9D End-to-end, not ju=
st the change you cherry-picked.</li>
  <li><strong>Cherry-picks of schema/data changes need extra scrutiny.</str=
ong> Migration logic written assuming a trunk DB state may break against a =
release DB state.</li>
  <li><strong>Prefer release-from-trunk over release-with-cherry-picks</str=
ong> when your cadence allows it - roughly weekly or faster. If you ship ev=
ery few days, a release branch buys you very little and the cherry-pick ove=
rhead isn=E2=80=99t worth it; just tag trunk. Cherry-picked release branche=
s earn their keep at monthly/quarterly cadences where the stabilization win=
dow is long enough that trunk has moved on substantially. Long-lived releas=
e branches that absorb selective fixes are a structural risk, not a tooling=
 problem git is going to grow out of.</li>
  <li><strong>For high-cost cherry-picks, run the full test suite on the ch=
erry-picked branch before merge.</strong> This is what the playground demon=
strates: a happy-path Selenium/Cypress/Playwright test that hits the UI and=
 asserts on the DB shows up regressions that <code class=3D"language-plaint=
ext highlighter-rouge">git diff</code> won=E2=80=99t.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"reproducing-this">Reproducing this</h2>

<div class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class=3D"highlight=
"><pre class=3D"highlight"><code>git clone https://github.com/paul-hammant/=
limits-of-merging-experiment
cd limits-of-merging-experiment
./start.sh                          # set up solution/ as a fresh playgroun=
d
./scenario-a-out-of-order.sh        # release: C2, C4, C3, then merge main
./rollback.sh
./scenario-b-in-order.sh            # release: C2, C3, C4, then merge main
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Each script prints the resulting graph, tree hash, and diff. Compare the=
 two.</p>

<p>The patches in <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">patc=
hes/</code> are real <code class=3D"language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">g=
it format-patch</code> output - readable, replayable, and the source of tru=
th for the trunk timeline. The scenario scripts pin author identity and tim=
estamps so anyone running them gets the same SHAs I did. That=E2=80=99s the=
 only way to make a cherry-pick experiment reproducible.</p>

<h2 id=3D"closing">Closing</h2>

<p>Cherry-pick is not infallible. It also isn=E2=80=99t usually wrong. The =
hazard is the gap between those two facts: <strong>git=E2=80=99s vocabulary=
 for =E2=80=9Cthis is the same change=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9Cthis is byte-ide=
ntical bytes,=E2=80=9D and outside of that narrow case, it has no opinion</=
strong>. SVN tried to fill that gap and is imperfect in it implementation. =
Git decided the mess wasn=E2=80=99t worth it.</p>

<p>What this means in practice for trunk-based development with release bra=
nches: cherry-pick is a tool that requires you to bring your own audit. The=
 audit is your=20
test suite, your code review, and your CI. If those are weak, cherry-pick i=
s a foot-gun. If they=E2=80=99re strong, cherry-pick is fine - and the SHA =
divergence between trunk and=20
release is just bookkeeping noise.</p>

<p>So per my colleagues nudge - cherry picks are great, but be careful and =
know the limits.</p>

<p>One last thing: I=E2=80=99ve been in engineering leadership previously f=
or a 12 planned releases a year team, and sometimes late features were merg=
ed to the release branch using=20
cherry-pick. Don=E2=80=99t do that - wait for the next release. I lost the =
argument cos the business really really wanted those late features - more t=
han once from the for the same=20
component of the system. Chery pick is for release stabilizing things only:=
 toggle off your work that isn=E2=80=99t ready to go live before the branch=
 cut moment.</p>

